{{zh-forms|s=号|alt=𠳯,虠,𭈹,号-ancient,呺-“to howl”}}

===Glyph origin===
{{Han etym}}
Originally an {{liushu|i|nocap=true}} of a tiger with a line representing exhaled air while roaring, thus meaning "to roar; to shout". Later forms added {{zh-l|*口|mouth}} or {{zh-l|*言|speech}} to emphasize the act of crying or calling. {{och-l|*号}} derives from {{lang|zh|口}} and the line {{och-l|*丂}}.

In the current form, an {{Han compound|号|虎|ls=ic|ls2=psc|c1=p|c2=s|t1=to wail|t2=tiger|nocap=y}}.

===Etymology===
From {{inh|zh|sit-pro|*kaw||to call}} ({{zh-ref|Schuessler, 2007}}, STEDT). Compare {{cog|kfk|ku||}}, {{cog|nun|go}}, and {{cog|my|ခေါ်}}. The extension of the meaning ‘shout, call’ to ‘ask, request’ is parallel to {{zh-l|呼}}.

Pronunciation 1 is the [[exopassive]] derivation of pronunciation 2, literally "what is called".

